<p class="body-text" style="margin-bottom:20px;">Three ideas across three different topic areas — one behavioral, one technological, one financial. Each example shows the complete decision-making process before the script. Read them as demonstrations of logic, not as templates to replicate.</p>

<!-- EXAMPLE 01 -->
<div class="subhead-sans" style="margin-top:0;">Example 01 &nbsp;—&nbsp; Behavioral</div>
<div class="callout" style="margin-bottom: 14px;">
<p>Idea: The reason most people can't focus has nothing to do with distraction — it has to do with how they start.</p>
</div>

<div style="border: 1px solid var(--rule); margin-bottom: 4px;">
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Start</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">Most advice about focus tells you to fix your environment. Remove the distractions. Put your phone in another room. Block the websites. And yet the people who follow all of that advice still find themselves not working. The problem was never the distraction. The problem is what happens in the three seconds before you reach for it.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Build</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">The standard model of focus failure positions distraction as the cause and attention management as the solution. This model is incomplete. There is a specific moment, familiar to almost everyone, where the task is in front of you and the first action hasn't happened yet. That moment doesn't feel like resistance. It feels like a small, sourceless hesitation. That hesitation is not distraction. It's avoidance. And it happens before the phone appears.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Shift</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">Distraction doesn't cause the loss of focus. It fills the space that avoidance already created. This reframes the entire problem. If distraction is the cause, the solution is environmental. But if distraction is a symptom — filling a space that will be filled regardless — then the intervention isn't the environment. It's the entry point. The three seconds after you sit down are where focus is won or lost. Everything else is downstream of that.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step">
<div class="ex-label"><span>End</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">You don't have a distraction problem. You have a starting problem. Fix the first three seconds, and the rest of the hour takes care of itself.</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
