<!-- EXAMPLE 02 -->
<div class="subhead-sans" style="margin-top:0;">Example 02 &nbsp;—&nbsp; Technological</div>
<div class="callout" style="margin-bottom: 14px;">
<p>Idea: The most consequential AI decisions today are not made by the AI — they are made by the people who designed the data it learned from.</p>
</div>
<div style="border: 1px solid var(--rule); margin-bottom: 24px;">
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Start</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">Every time an AI system makes a decision about your loan, your medical scan, or the content you see — someone tells you the algorithm did it. That framing is technically accurate and functionally misleading. The algorithm executed a decision. The decision itself was made years earlier, by people you've never heard of, about data you've never seen.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Build</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">Before training data exists as data, someone decided what to include, what to exclude, how to label it, and what outcomes to treat as correct. These decisions reflect the categories those people worked with, the cases they treated as representative, the edge cases they considered too rare to include. By the time a system is deployed and audited, those choices are embedded in the model's weights — invisible in the output, unreachable by conventional review.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Shift</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">The standard model of AI accountability positions human oversight at the deployment end: humans monitor outputs and intervene when the system errs. This model assumes the machine is the source of the problem. But if the problem is in the training data — introduced before the model existed — end-stage oversight is auditing the consequence of a decision already made. The machine is not making biased decisions. It is faithfully reproducing the judgments of people who made biased decisions about data.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step">
<div class="ex-label"><span>End</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">The right question to ask about any AI system is not how it makes decisions. It is whose judgments it was built to reproduce — and whether those people knew, when they made them, that the decisions would matter this much.</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- EXAMPLE 03 — condensed -->
<div class="subhead-sans" style="margin-top:0;">Example 03 &nbsp;—&nbsp; Financial</div>
<div class="callout" style="margin-bottom: 14px;">
<p>Idea: Inflation doesn't affect everyone equally — it functions as a wealth transfer mechanism, and the direction of the transfer is almost never discussed.</p>
</div>
<div style="border: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Start</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">Inflation is described as rising prices. That description is accurate and almost completely uninformative. What inflation actually does — as a mechanism, not a weather event — is move value from one group of people to another. The direction of that movement is not random. It follows the structure of asset ownership.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Build</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">While cash loses purchasing power during an inflationary period, real assets typically increase in nominal value — not because they became more productive, but because the unit of measurement lost value. The asset holder ends the period with the same asset, now denominated in more dollars. The cash holder ends with the same dollars, now worth fewer assets.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step" style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
<div class="ex-label"><span>Shift</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">The capacity to hold wealth in real assets rather than cash is not a behavioral choice available equally to everyone — it is a function of prior wealth. The same mechanism, operating simultaneously, produces opposite outcomes. That is not a coincidence. It is how the mechanism works.</div>
</div>
<div class="example-step">
<div class="ex-label"><span>End</span></div>
<div class="ex-text">Inflation is a pump — and it moves value in a direction determined not by the market, but by the structure of who owns what.</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
