<div class="content">
<div class="section-label">
<div class="sec-num">08</div>
<div class="sec-title-group">
<div class="sec-tag">Diagnostic</div>
<div class="sec-title">Common Mistakes</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sec-rule"></div>

<p class="body-text" style="margin-bottom:20px;">Every mistake in video content can be traced back to a specific point in the four-step structure. When a video isn't working, the problem is almost always one of these.</p>

<div class="mistake-block">
<div class="mistake-header">
<div class="mistake-num">01 — Start</div>
<div class="mistake-title">Starting with context instead of tension</div>
</div>
<p class="body-text" style="font-size:11px;">Context relaxes the viewer. Tension holds them. A viewer who receives context before the hook has been given everything they need to decide the video isn't for them. The fix is almost always structural: the strong opening is already in the video — it's just not at the beginning. Move the tension to the first line. Move the context to the BUILD.</p>
</div>

<div class="mistake-block">
<div class="mistake-header">
<div class="mistake-num">02 — Build</div>
<div class="mistake-title">Building too wide instead of too deep</div>
</div>
<p class="body-text" style="font-size:11px;">Multiple examples of the same point feel like coverage from inside the topic and feel like stagnation from outside it. The viewer already received the point and is waiting for something to develop. Test each paragraph: did the viewer's understanding genuinely advance, or do they simply have more evidence for something they understood two paragraphs ago?</p>
</div>

<div class="mistake-block">
<div class="mistake-header">
<div class="mistake-num">03 — Shift</div>
<div class="mistake-title">The shift that isn't one</div>
</div>
<p class="body-text" style="font-size:11px;">New information doesn't produce a SHIFT. A change in the frame through which existing information is seen produces a SHIFT. The most common version: the video explains an idea, then at the SHIFT point explains more of the same idea — more deeply, but without changing the angle. The viewer learned more. They did not see differently. Finding the real SHIFT requires pushing past the first answer — the one that extends the BUILD comfortably.</p>
</div>

<div class="mistake-block">
<div class="mistake-header">
<div class="mistake-num">04 — End</div>
<div class="mistake-title">Ending after the video is already over</div>
</div>
<p class="body-text" style="font-size:11px;">Most weak endings share one feature: the video ended one or two sentences before the creator stopped. There was a moment where the arc completed — and then the creator continued, adding a summary or restatement. The viewer's final impression is not the strong moment. It's whatever diluted it. Identify where the arc genuinely completes. Stop there.</p>
</div>

<div class="mistake-block" style="border-bottom:none; padding-bottom:0;">
<div class="mistake-header">
<div class="mistake-num">05 — Build → Shift</div>
<div class="mistake-title">Losing momentum in the middle</div>
</div>
<p class="body-text" style="font-size:11px;">The BUILD has a natural tendency to decelerate as it completes. The creator begins to summarize rather than maintain forward pressure. The SHIFT then arrives into a lower state of engagement. Treat the final movement of the BUILD as an acceleration, not a landing. The last sentence of the BUILD should bring the viewer to the edge of the question the SHIFT will answer — close enough to feel it, not close enough to see the answer.</p>
</div>

</div>
